node.text:
From today’s IGLive chat. 

Community: How are you walking in your purpose? 

If you’re unsure of what that purpose is or how to get there, there’s a tip in this video on how to explore the path you want to make for yourself. 

Looking forward to your thoughts and comments here. 

#selfcare / #mindbodysoul / #purposedrivenlife / #selfhealing

node.title: Refusing to Settle + Walking in Purpose

node.text:
In celebration and anticipation of @aftertherainbook, I sat down today with my friend, Lisa (@_lisaolivera) to discuss moving through our pain vs. ignoring it, self-trust, and finding ways to reshape our narrative as we heal and grow.
.
.
After the Rain is out on 10/13! Pre-order at the link in my bio.

node.text:
Affirmations for us:

You will and can return to yourself.
Healing might feel like it's too much to bear—that's okay. Remember that you are built for it.
Self-love is an act of healing and an act of blooming inside of your body.
If it doesn't elevate or support your growth, I would like you to consider letting it go.

If you feel like you want to give up, hold on a little tighter. If you feel like you can't do it, lean into self-belief a little harder. 

Community, I see you. Share this with whoever you think may need it.

node.text:
Don't let anyone tell you that you can't create the life you want—even if that person is you.

Here's some real-talk motivation for your week ahead. 

Some time ago, I put on my intentions list that I wanted to take my teaching a step further by being a teacher in residence somewhere. Big or small. Didn't matter to me. I just wanted to show up in a new way, serve folks in an intimate setting, and teach anyone who wanted to learn the benefits of writing to heal.

That intention to be a teacher in residence somewhere sat on my list for a long time. I had no idea where to start. To be honest, I was intimidated. Thoughts of doubt crept in—even though I'd been teaching. Even though I knew exactly what I was doing. The inner critic is an interesting thing and, if we are open enough, a great teacher. 

Long story short, I almost talked myself out of this possibility. But instead, I leaned in. Leaning in got me the opportunity to start my first ever teacher in residency in Carefree, AZ at @civanaresort—where I visited with my husband and our friends—@nnekaj + @cortneyisms this weekend.

Leaning in encouraged self-trust. 

I am so grateful for growth. 
I am so grateful to be exercising self-trust.
I am so grateful that my inner critic is no longer allowed to lead my life.
I am so grateful to be living the life I dream of. One that is rooted in intention, love, and ease.

So to anyone struggling with something similar, you aren't the only one. 
To anyone feeling like their dreams are unrealistic, they are as real as you make them.

To anyone who has set an intention on their list that hasn't come to be [yet], keep working on it and at it. 

Doubt is a part of the human experience, whether internal or external—and so is perseverance. 

My residency at Civana starts 12/29. I will be there every quarter for about 2 weeks at a time. Learn more at the link in my bio, and join me as we Write to Heal and learn how to use breathwork to get back into our bodies and find emotional clarity. 

I hope to see you there.

Community: What intentions are on your list that you'd like to see come to fruition? What intentions have already manifested?

#civanacarefree / #healingjourney

node.text:
Gentle reminder for the rest of the week.

I made the decision to break up with a friend this year. It was hard but necessary. Last night, I thought about them. I wondered how they were doing and feeling these days. A big part of me wanted to reach out and check in but I decided not to.

The tail end of our friendship I was manipulated and really hurt by them. And while relationships are complicated and can sometimes be salvaged, I knew last night that reaching out wouldn’t be healthy or supportive to my emotional well-being. 

I’m also not interested in being friends again. And that’s okay. For some months, I felt awful for feeling that way. But realizing that two things can exist at once is a great teacher. We can wonder how folks are doing and hope they’re doing well, and not want to rekindle the relationship. 

So instead, I sent them a loving thought from afar, smiled about the last time we had lunch, and went to bed. 

Sometimes rekindling isn’t the right move. We can reflect and think about the good times without reconnecting.

Community: What are you normalizing when parting ways and moving on?

node.text:
I remember when I used to think I was a nobody…

Now I'm living in my purpose—liberated and rooted in self-love.

What changed? I did.

Change started with a choice not to allow:
settling
self-loathing
daddy/mommy issues
trauma
low vibrational behavior/relationships
mental health challenges
and pain

be the place where I rested.

For years, I made a home out of my hurt. For years, I struggled to find my way, my footing, myself. One thing that was consistent in my life was me. My ah-ha moment was waking up to self-value + self-worth.

If you've read @aftertherainbook, you know quite a bit about my story and how I got to where I am in my healing. My healing has been my sacred choice. If you've been in community with me for a while, you're familiar with that statement.

For anyone struggling right now, no matter your life walk, I hope you trust that joy is an option—even after deep pain. I hope you remember that self-healing and emotional clarity is an option. It may feel hard as hell today—and that's OK. Beginning again can start tomorrow.

Over the past year, I've committed myself to deeper healing via learning and teaching. Last week I completed my Breathwork Teacher Training. Starting at the end of this year, I'll be a teacher in
residence at an amazing retreat center in Arizona. I've worked so hard to get to a place where self-belief overshadowed self-doubt and external negative chatter. Healing is a daily practice. I am looking forward to serving this community and beyond through breathwork and writing practice. I'm looking forward to sharing space and stories. 

I remember when I used to think I was a nobody.

Now I'm committed to my purpose—liberated and rooted in healing.

If you're reading this and feeling lost, you are not alone. Don't give up on yourself. You can heal. You can grow through the pain. You can flourish. 

Community: What is your sacred choice? 

#healthychanges / #mindsetmatters / 
#personalgrowth / #selfnurture / #healing

Kindness is not to be confused with:

-having no boundaries
-tolerating unhealthy behavior
-letting people belittle you

You can be loving, kind, understanding, and compassionate without letting folks treat you poorly. Protecting your peace and space also means being very clear about what you will and will not tolerate.

node.text:
Ruminating on my past kept me from moving forward for years. Staying stuck in the cycles of negative self-talk kept me from being my best self. As I started to grow and learn more about the relationship I wanted to have with myself, I became committed to living a life that didn't hold me hostage or stuck in shame. Mistakes, shortcomings, and failures happen—that is a part of our human experience. We cannot avoid them, but we can grow from them. Each misstep taught me resilience. Choosing not to stay stuck in the past gave me the permission I needed to grow forward and do better.
 
My #oathtoself of the week is: I am not my past—moving forward is the future.

Community: What have you learned about moving forward and not staying stuck in the past?
